{{Infobox organization |name = International Braille Chess Association |image = International Braille Chess Association Logo.gif |size = 150 |caption = IBCA logo |abbreviation = IBCA |formation = 1958<ref name="ibcahist"/> |type = [[International nongovernmental organization|INGO]] |headquarters = [[Homberg (Efze)|Homberg]], [[Germany]]<ref name="FIDE"/> |language = <!-- official languages --> |leader_title = President |leader_name = [[Ludwig Beutelhoff]]<ref name="FIDE">[https://ratings.fide.com/fide_directory.phtml?list=964 International Braille Chess Association at FIDE.com]</ref> |affiliations = [[FIDE]], [[International Blind Sports Federation|IBSA]] |website = {{URL|https://www.ibca-info.org}} }}
The '''International Braille Chess Association''' ('''IBCA''') is organization for [[Blindness|blind]] and [[visually impaired]] [[chess]] players. The IBCA is a [[FIDE]]-affiliated chess organization as well as a part of the [[International Blind Sports Federation]]. The International Braille Chess Association originated informally in 1951 with the organization of the first international correspondence chess tournament for blind players, by [[Reginald Walter Bonham]]; the tournament included 20 players representing 10 countries. It first organized an over-the-board tournament in 1958, with representatives from seven countries. Today, it has grown to encompass over 50 member nations around the world.<ref name="ibcahist">[http://www.schachkomet.de/ibcabuch.htm History of the IBCA] Retrieved January 30, 2016</ref> The IBCA hosts two major competitions: the [[Blind Chess Olympiad]] and the [[Blind World Chess Championship]].
==Rule modifications== Although most of the rules in blind chess are consistent with [[Rules of chess|normal chess]], there are a few modifications to the equipment to aid blind and visually impaired players:<ref name="rules"> [https://www.ibca-info.org/rules-of-chess.php Rules of Chess] Retrieved September 12, 2018</ref><ref> [https://www.ibca-info.org/how-visually-impaired-play-chess.asp How the Visually Impaired Play Chess] Retrieved September 7, 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.eyeway.org/?q=chess Chess - Eyeway.org] Retrieved September 9, 2014</ref> # Either player may demand the use of two boards, the sighted player using a normal board, the visually handicapped player using a board that is specially constructed as follows: # All the black squares are raised about 3–4&nbsp;mm above the white squares on the [[chessboard]]. By feeling the squares, the player is able to determine whether the square is a black or a white one. # Each of the squares on the board has a hole in the center so that the [[chess piece]]s can be fixed in these holes. # Each of the pieces has a downward projection (nail) at the base, which fits into the hole in the squares on the board, thereby fixing the piece securely on the board. # All the black pieces have a pin fixed on their heads helping the player distinguish between a white and a black piece.
After making every move, each player is required to announce their move aloud to their opponent. Instead of writing the moves on a [[Score sheet (chess)|chess score sheet]], the visually impaired player writes the moves in [[Braille]] or records the moves on a [[tape recorder]].<ref name="rules"/>
